+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01MR9zTWhkkaigAVjFuueikV","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"There's a lex-ordering issue. The problem is that during Gaussian elimination, when button 0 and button 1 both toggle light 0, one of them becomes the pivot and the other becomes free. Button 0 is the pivot column, so it gets set based on the free variable (button 1). When the free variable button 1 = 0, the pivot button 0 = 1. When free variable button 1 = 1, pivot button 0 = 0. So the result [1] (pressing button 1) has the same count as [0] (pressing button 0), but is lexicographically larger. The issue is my `lexSmaller` function is comparing 0/1 vectors — [0,1] vs [1,0]. [0,1] is indeed lex smaller than [1,0], so the solution should be button 1. Let me re-examine:\n\nWait — the result `[1]` means pressing button index 1. The result `[0]` means pressing button index 0. As *sorted index arrays*, `[0]` < `[1]` lexicographically. But my comparison is on the 0/1 vector: `[1,0]` vs `[0,1]`. In vector form, `[0,1] < [1,0]`, so button 1 is preferred. But the spec says return sorted button indices, and `[0] < [1]` as sorted arrays.\n\nThe spec says \"lexicographically smallest set of indices.\" So `{0}` < `{1}`. The comparison should be on the sorted index arrays, which means we compare the 0/1 vector representation where a smaller index having a 1 makes it \"smaller.\" Actually `{0}` as indices = `[0]`, `{1}` as indices = `[1]`. `[0]` < `[1]` lex. So we should prefer button 0.\n\nBut my vector comparison `lexSmaller([1,0], [0,1])` returns `false` (first element 1 > 0). So it picks `[0,1]` vector (button 1) instead. The fix: my lex comparison on 0/1 vectors should prefer `[1,0]` over `[0,1]` when they have the same count, because in index-set form, `{0}` < `{1}`. Actually, the 0/1 vector approach is wrong for lex comparison of index sets. `{0}` = [1,0] and `{1}` = [0,1]. As index lists: [0] < [1]. But as vecto